</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="37956579FF8AFFD0FF5FFCA3FC9948C1" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="7F3036F2FF8AFFD0FF5FFCA3FEB74872" blockId="29.[151,1437,865,2006]" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">
<emphasis id="4DFBEAE0FF8AFFD0FF5FFCA3FEFC4F59" bold="true" box="[151,266,865,890]" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">Diagnosis</emphasis>
. A monotypic lyttine genus (
<figureCitation id="E7B42A77FF8AFFD0FDACFCA3FD484F59" box="[612,702,865,890]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="12.[151,250,1854,1876]" captionTargetBox="[189,1378,291,1822]" captionTargetId="figure@12.[147,1432,249,1842]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="FIGURE 1. A. Iselma deserticola; B. Iselma hobohmi; C. Iselma penrithae; D. Iselma brunneipes. E. Iselma piscatrix; F. Eletica luteosignata. G. Namibeletica angolana; H. Namibeletica elegantula; I. Afrolytta namaqua; J. Afrolytta amoena; K. Afrolytta carneola; L. Australytta maraisi; M. Australytta rubrolineata; N. Australytta szekessyi; O. Australytta vellicata; P. Lydomorphus chalybaeus; Q. Lydomorphus mimus; R. Lydomorphus bisignatus; S. Lydomorphus strangulatus; T. Lydomorphus karibibensis; U. Lydomorphus thoracicus; V. Lydomorphus tibialis; W. Lydomorphus bifoveiceps; X. Dilatilydus optatus; Y. Desertilydus mesembryanthemi." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1151726/files/figure.png" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">Fig. 1Y</figureCitation>
) similar in shape to 
<taxonomicName id="B88F4D71FF8AFFD0FC7EFCA3FAE64F59" authority="Fairmaire, 1882" authorityName="Fairmaire" authorityYear="1882" box="[950,1296,865,890]" class="Insecta" family="Meloidae" genus="Lydomorphus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="4DFBEAE0FF8AFFD0FC7EFCA3FBB94F5A" box="[950,1103,865,889]" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">Lydomorphus</emphasis>
Fairmaire, 1882
</taxonomicName>
particularly because of the slender body and pronotum, but greatly distinct because of the head dorsally almost flat, eyes ventrally not extended medianly under head, antennae very short in both sexes not reaching base of pronotum, male last ventrite lacking apical laminar expansions, male gonostyli well sclerotized, body setation reduced. 
<taxonomicName id="B88F4D71FF8AFFD0FF5FFC33FED2482A" authority="Bologna &amp; Amore &amp; Pitzalis, 2018" authorityName="Bologna &amp; Amore &amp; Pitzalis" authorityYear="2018" box="[151,292,1009,1033]" class="Insecta" family="Meloidae" genus="Desertilydus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="29" pageNumber="8" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus" status="gen. n">
<emphasis id="4DFBEAE0FF8AFFD0FF5FFC33FED2482A" box="[151,292,1009,1033]" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">Desertilydus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
differs from the new genus 
<taxonomicName id="B88F4D71FF8AFFD0FDBDFC33FD04482A" authority="Bologna &amp; Amore &amp; Pitzalis, 2018" authorityName="Bologna &amp; Amore &amp; Pitzalis" authorityYear="2018" box="[629,754,1009,1033]" class="Insecta" family="Meloidae" genus="Dilatilydus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="29" pageNumber="8" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus" status="gen. n">
<emphasis id="4DFBEAE0FF8AFFD0FDBDFC33FD04482A" box="[629,754,1009,1033]" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">Dilatilydus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
because of the head almost flat dorsally and the antennae greatly shorter and male gonoforceps wider and narrowed only in apical third, not curved posteriad, and body scarcely setate.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="7F3036F2FF8AFFD0FF0FFB9FFC9948C1" blockId="29.[151,1437,865,2006]" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">
The type species, endemic to Namibian and South African Namaqualand and to northern Karoo, was referred by 
<bibRefCitation id="1B1E4B03FF8AFFD0FF73FB43FDB148B9" author="Kaszab" box="[187,583,1153,1178]" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" refString="Kaszab, Z. (1955 a) Die Arten der Meloiden-Gattung Cylindrothorax Escher. (Coleoptera). Annales historico-naturales Musei nationalis Hungarici, New Series, 6, 225 - 258." type="journal article" year="1955" yearSuffix="a">
Kaszab (1955a, as 
<taxonomicName id="B88F4D71FF8AFFD0FE5BFB43FDC948BA" box="[403,575,1153,1177]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Cylindrothorax" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="4DFBEAE0FF8AFFD0FE5BFB43FDC948BA" box="[403,575,1153,1177]" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">Cylindrothorax</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
)
</bibRefCitation>
to a distinct group (XXII). We herein refer it to a new genus, well distinct from 
<taxonomicName id="B88F4D71FF8AFFD0FF12FB67FE85489E" authorityName="Fairmaire" authorityYear="1882" box="[218,371,1189,1213]" class="Insecta" family="Meloidae" genus="Lydomorphus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="4DFBEAE0FF8AFFD0FF12FB67FE85489E" box="[218,371,1189,1213]" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">Lydomorphus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
at least by the shape of last male ventrite without laminar expansion; eyes not extended ventrally, head dorsally very flat, antennae very short and robust.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="37956579FF8AFFD0FF0FFB2FFB9B4BF5" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" type="description">
<paragraph id="7F3036F2FF8AFFD0FF0FFB2FFBBB49B6" blockId="29.[151,1437,865,2006]" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">
<emphasis id="4DFBEAE0FF8AFFD0FF0FFB2FFEA74925" bold="true" box="[199,337,1261,1286]" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">Description</emphasis>
. Characters of the 
<typeStatus id="A0348850FF8AFFD0FDE6FB2CFDA84925" box="[558,606,1262,1286]" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">type</typeStatus>
species. Body ochre, but ventral and lateral sides of head, antennae and mouthparts, legs and usually episternites and a narrow portion of elytral apex black (
<figureCitation id="E7B42A77FF8AFFD0FBADFAD3FB364909" box="[1125,1216,1297,1322]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="12.[151,250,1854,1876]" captionTargetBox="[189,1378,291,1822]" captionTargetId="figure@12.[147,1432,249,1842]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="FIGURE 1. A. Iselma deserticola; B. Iselma hobohmi; C. Iselma penrithae; D. Iselma brunneipes. E. Iselma piscatrix; F. Eletica luteosignata. G. Namibeletica angolana; H. Namibeletica elegantula; I. Afrolytta namaqua; J. Afrolytta amoena; K. Afrolytta carneola; L. Australytta maraisi; M. Australytta rubrolineata; N. Australytta szekessyi; O. Australytta vellicata; P. Lydomorphus chalybaeus; Q. Lydomorphus mimus; R. Lydomorphus bisignatus; S. Lydomorphus strangulatus; T. Lydomorphus karibibensis; U. Lydomorphus thoracicus; V. Lydomorphus tibialis; W. Lydomorphus bifoveiceps; X. Dilatilydus optatus; Y. Desertilydus mesembryanthemi." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1151726/files/figure.png" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">Fig. 1Y</figureCitation>
). Dorsal surface of head and pronotum glabrous, elytra with short and scattered dark setae, ventral surface with dark short setae denser than on dorsal surface, very dense on coxae and throchanters. Elytra not covering completely the abdomen, especially in female but also in some males. Body sligthly obtuse, length 
<quantity id="B8779B17FF8AFFD0FC06FABFFBBF49B6" box="[974,1097,1405,1430]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.3" metricValueMax="1.5" metricValueMin="1.1" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" unit="mm" value="13.0" valueMax="15.0" valueMin="11.0">11â15 mm</quantity>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="7F3036F2FF8AFFD0FF0FFA63FD7C4B02" blockId="29.[151,1437,865,2006]" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">Head shortly subrectangular, with temples parallel in both sexes widely curved posteriorly, sligthly shorter than longitudinal diameter of eye. Mandibles longer than labrum, at apex narrowed and pointed; maxillary and labial palpomeres not modified; clypeus greatly shorter than labrum, labrum at apex almost straigth or scarcely emarginated. Antennae short and not modified in both sexes. Male antennomere I sligthly shorter than III, more than two times II; II very short and subglobose; IIIâXI cylindrical, III about 1.5 times as long as IV, IVâX similar in length; XI cylindrical but greatly narrower in apical third and pointed at apex with dense small yellow setae. Female antennomeres similar to those of male, just scarcely more submoniliform, but last antennomere slightly less narrowed. Pronotum narrow and slender, suboval, slightly converging in fore third, without dorsal depressions. Thoracic ventrites not modified. Elytral external margin in lateral view sligthly emarginated in middle. Legs non modified in both sexes; tarsomeres without ventral pads; pro- and metatibial spurs elongate and pointed, metatibial external spur spoon-like not pointed at apex.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="7F3036F2FF8AFFD0FF0FF8EFFB9B4BF5" blockId="29.[151,1437,865,2006]" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">Ventrites not modified; last male sternite V-emarginated, longitudinally depressed in middle, without laminar expansions, that of female not emarginated. Male genitalia with gonoforceps longer than gonocoxal base, wider and parallel in the basal 2/3, narrowed at apex, with a wide depressed oval area on dorsal fore portion, not curved posteriad, dispersely setate, particularly on dorsal side of apical third, and with spiniform setae on ventral side at apex; aedeagus with two pointed and thin hooks both far from apex, subequal in length.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="37956579FF89FFD3FF0FFF55FB204CDB" pageId="30" pageNumber="31" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="7F3036F2FF89FFD3FF0FFF55FB204CDB" blockId="30.[151,1436,151,501]" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">
<emphasis id="4DFBEAE0FF89FFD3FF0FFF55FEB84C93" bold="true" box="[199,334,151,176]" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">Etymology.</emphasis>
The name of the new genus refers to its ecological relation to southern African desert ecosystems (mainly Namib, Nama and Succulent Karoo), and is composed also by 
<taxonomicName id="B88F4D71FF89FFD3FC7BFF7EFC034CF7" box="[947,1013,188,212]" class="Insecta" family="Meloidae" genus="Lydus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="30" pageNumber="31" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="4DFBEAE0FF89FFD3FC7BFF7EFC034CF7" box="[947,1013,188,212]" italics="true" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">Lydus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, the name of another lyttine genus, in assonance with the name of two subgenera of 
<taxonomicName id="B88F4D71FF89FFD3FD53FF22FCC24CDB" authorityName="Fairmaire" authorityYear="1882" box="[667,820,224,248]" class="Insecta" family="Meloidae" genus="Lydomorphus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="30" pageNumber="31" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="4DFBEAE0FF89FFD3FD53FF22FCC24CDB" box="[667,820,224,248]" italics="true" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">Lydomorphus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and to 
<taxonomicName id="B88F4D71FF89FFD3FC4FFF22FBF54CDB" authority="Bologna &amp; Amore &amp; Pitzalis, 2018" authorityName="Bologna &amp; Amore &amp; Pitzalis" authorityYear="2018" box="[903,1027,224,248]" class="Insecta" family="Meloidae" genus="Dilatilydus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="30" pageNumber="8" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus" status="gen. n">
<emphasis id="4DFBEAE0FF89FFD3FC4FFF22FBF54CDB" box="[903,1027,224,248]" italics="true" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">Dilatilydus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Masculine genus.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="37956579FF89FFD3FF0FFEC6FC304DD7" pageId="30" pageNumber="31" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="7F3036F2FF89FFD3FF0FFEC6FEA44DF3" blockId="30.[151,1436,151,501]" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">
<emphasis id="4DFBEAE0FF89FFD3FF0FFEC6FECD4D3E" bold="true" box="[199,315,260,285]" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">Remarks.</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="1B1E4B03FF89FFD3FE8CFEC6FE014D3E" author="Kaszab" box="[324,503,260,285]" pageId="30" pageNumber="31" refString="Kaszab, Z. (1955 a) Die Arten der Meloiden-Gattung Cylindrothorax Escher. (Coleoptera). Annales historico-naturales Musei nationalis Hungarici, New Series, 6, 225 - 258." type="journal article" year="1955" yearSuffix="a">Kaszab (1955a)</bibRefCitation>
pointed out the very distinct position of this species. Affinities of this genus are completely unkwnon, even if, according to molecular analyses (Pitzalis 
<emphasis id="4DFBEAE0FF89FFD3FC1AFEEBFBFA4D63" box="[978,1036,296,320]" italics="true" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">et al.</emphasis>
in preparation), it appears isolated and very distinct from 
<taxonomicName id="B88F4D71FF89FFD3FE53FE8EFDC24D47" authorityName="Fairmaire" authorityYear="1882" box="[411,564,332,356]" class="Insecta" family="Meloidae" genus="Lydomorphus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="30" pageNumber="31" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="4DFBEAE0FF89FFD3FE53FE8EFDC24D47" box="[411,564,332,356]" italics="true" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">Lydomorphus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and from another Saharo-Sahelian new lineage of 
<taxonomicName id="B88F4D71FF89FFD3FBBFFE8EFB344D46" authorityName="Bologna &amp; Amore &amp; Pitzalis" authorityYear="2018" box="[1143,1218,332,357]" class="Insecta" family="Meloidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="30" pageNumber="31" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" tribe="Lyttini">Lyttini</taxonomicName>
similar in shape to 
<taxonomicName id="B88F4D71FF89FFD3FF5FFEB2FEC64DAB" authorityName="Fairmaire" authorityYear="1882" box="[151,304,368,392]" class="Insecta" family="Meloidae" genus="Lydomorphus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="30" pageNumber="31" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="4DFBEAE0FF89FFD3FF5FFEB2FEC64DAB" box="[151,304,368,392]" italics="true" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">Lydomorphus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. As both this last taxon and 
<taxonomicName id="B88F4D71FF89FFD3FDB4FEB2FD0E4DAB" authority="Bologna &amp; Amore &amp; Pitzalis, 2018" authorityName="Bologna &amp; Amore &amp; Pitzalis" authorityYear="2018" box="[636,760,368,392]" class="Insecta" family="Meloidae" genus="Dilatilydus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="30" pageNumber="8" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus" status="gen. n">
<emphasis id="4DFBEAE0FF89FFD3FDB4FEB2FD0E4DAB" box="[636,760,368,392]" italics="true" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">Dilatilydus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, it lacks the shared condition of modified last ventrite (see above). The general shape of pronotum and male genitalia seems more similar to that of 
<taxonomicName id="B88F4D71FF89FFD3FBB8FE56FAFF4D8F" authorityName="Fairmaire" authorityYear="1882" box="[1136,1289,404,428]" class="Insecta" family="Meloidae" genus="Lydomorphus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="30" pageNumber="31" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="4DFBEAE0FF89FFD3FBB8FE56FAFF4D8F" box="[1136,1289,404,428]" italics="true" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">Lydomorphus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
than to other genera of 
<taxonomicName id="B88F4D71FF89FFD3FECFFE75FEA44DF3" authorityName="Bologna &amp; Amore &amp; Pitzalis" authorityYear="2018" box="[263,338,439,464]" class="Insecta" family="Meloidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="30" pageNumber="31" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" tribe="Lyttini">Lyttini</taxonomicName>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="7F3036F2FF89FFD3FF0FFE1EFC304DD7" blockId="30.[151,1436,151,501]" box="[199,966,476,501]" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">
